text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!SignLanguage]]%0a%0a!Phonology in Sign Language%0a%0a:Author: khushiw%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aPhonology in sign language can be narrowed down to a select few features: hand configuration, movement, and location.%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aPhonology in sign language can be narrowed down to a select few features: hand configuration, movement, and location. When a word has a singular morpheme, it has all fingers extended, closed, curved, or bent. The handshapes can also be considered marked or unmarked. Less marked words/sounds are usually easier to sign and produce. Orientation of the hand, such as whether the palm is facing up or down, can also have an impact on the phonology of a word in sign language. Next, location is a major element in sign language. Each free morpheme is dedicated to a certain part of the body. Location can also be in relation to the morpheme that precedes the current one. This is usually for common words that have frequently used paths. This is because it is easier than having to go from your arm, to your torso, to your head. Finally, movement is an essential part of the phonology of words in sign language. Lexical signs can be attributed to specific series of movements. This often involves morphemes moving to locations in relation to one another, rather than specific locations. Movement also includes the movement of two hands or the repeated movement of one hand. Movement is considered the most important way to distinguish between and move to the next syllable in words. %0a%0aSource: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3608481/ %0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 210507-022737-575600#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Facial Expressions %0a-> - AlexanderW%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aThough not phonology, facial expressions are extremely important in conveying the meaning and intent behind the signed sentences and questions.%0a%0aIn any sign language, facial expressions do 2 major things. First, in most languages, an eyebrow raise denotes a question mark. Secondly, facial expressions are used to express emotion - sort of like how, when we speak, we emphasize and speed/slow down certain words, or we use the quality of speech to denote sarcasm.%0a%0aAs the study referenced in this expansion mentions, when combining questions with different emotions, the facial expressions get combined, and thus get quite complex. The reason why this study is so important is in computer translation. As facial expressions can vary only a little bit and mean vastly different things, a computer has to be extraordinarily accurate in detecting minute changes in body and head position, eyebrow position, and how the signing and face interact.%0a%0ahttps://www.uib.no/en/hf/136874/complex-system-facial-expressions-sign-language#:~:text=%2522In%2520sign%2520language%252C%2520facial%2520expressions,or%2520when%2520quoting%2520someone%2520else.%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210507-022737-575600#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: B:)%0a(:Category: SignLanguage:)
